for 0 < p < 1 and when x1 and x2 get closer to each other, the inequality becomes weaker. This inequality statement can be re-phrased by considering x as a random variable. The value of a convex function at the mean value of x is smaller than the mean value of the function:





where 〈∙〉 represents the mean value. When the value of x is less noisy (smaller randomness), the inequality becomes weaker. This indicates that the output mean value can be dependent on the strength of the input signal noise. Thus, when averaging cellular signals over the cell population, the population responses can be significantly different from the individual cellular responses due to interplay between stochasticity and nonlinearity.
